         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">London ¶ 25, WILTON PLACE, S.W. ¶ May 18/63 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ Enclosed is the bill of lading of the four cases sent pr Prince of Wales. I hope to hear of their reaching you in safety...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">63.05.18</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Garden Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation by M: 'Promised <name key="Rosaceae">Rosaceae</name>, <name key="Lythraceae">Lythraceae</name>, Saxifragiae, Melastomeae, Lytheraceae, Combretaceae, Rhizophoreae'. See M to G. Bentham, 23 July 1863.</p>
               </note>London</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">May 18/63</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Enclosed is the bill of lading of the four cases sent pr Prince of Wales. I hope to hear of their reaching you in safety</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By this mail I send you the remainder of the first vol. of my Flora Australiensis<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 1. Bentham was sending sheets as they were printed; see G. Bentham to M, 12 February 1863 (in this edition as 63-02-12a).</p>
               </note> I will put up the 30 copies your Government is entitled to in the next box I send you.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am now at <name key="Papilionaceae">Papilionaceae</name> I have done <name key="Jansonia">Jansonia</name> a good genus with 1 species, <name key="Brachysema">Brachysema</name> with 13 species including <name key="Leptosema">Leptosema</name>
               <name key="Kaleniczenkea">Kaleniczenkea</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="color: #000000; font-style: italic; ">Kaleniczenkia</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #000000; ">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> and <name key="Burgesia">Burgesia</name>, Oxylobium with 26 species including Callistachys and <name key="Podolobium">Podolobium</name>. <name key="Gastrolobium">Gastrolobium</name> with 29 species Chorizema with 13 species including <name key="Orthotropis">Orthotropis</name> and Mirbelia with 15 species including <name key="Dichosema">Dichosema</name> and Isotropis with 5 species.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 1 includes more species than are listed here: <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Brachysema">Brachysema</name>
                     </seg> with 14, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Oxylobium</seg>, 27; <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Gastrolobium">Gastrolobium</name>
                     </seg>, 32; <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Chorizema</seg>, 15; <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Mirbelia</seg>, 16; <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Isotropis</seg>, 7. </p>
               </note> In all I have been obliged to reduce many species I had previously published — <name key="Oxylobium%20arborescens">Oxylobium arborescens</name> and your O. alpestre (which I do not quote as not being published)<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M had published <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Oxylobium%20alpestre">Oxylobium alpestre</name>
                     </seg>in B55.09.02, p. 38, the source cited by Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2, p. 17 when he treated it as a distinct species. See M to G. Bentham, 11 August 1863.</p>
               </note> go into O. ellipticum. I include <name key="Callistachys%20lanceolata">Callistachys lanceolata</name> and ovata in one species O. callistachys <name key="Isotropis%20biloba">Isotropis biloba</name> is a var of I. striata <name key="Oxylobium%20obovatum">Oxylobium obovatum</name> &amp; O. delalatum<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">O. dilatatum</seg>?</p>
               </note> go into O. cuneatum <name key="Chorizema%20Baueri">Chorizema Baueri</name> is <name key="Mirbelia%20pungens">Mirbelia pungens</name>
               <name key="Dichosema%20spinosum">Dichosema spinosum</name> Bth &amp; D. subinerne Meisn. <seg style="">= <name key="Mirbelia%20spinosa">Mirbelia spinosa</name> D. multicaulis</seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">D. multicaule</seg>?</p>
               </note>
               <seg style=""> Turcz = M. multicaulis D. microphyllum Turcz. </seg>= M. microphylla, <name key="Chorizema%20daviesioides">Chorizema daviesioides</name> Meisn. or <name key="Daviesia%20ramulosa">Daviesia ramulosa</name> Bth = <name key="Mirbelia%20daviesioides">Mirbelia daviesioides</name> besides many other reductions but still the collections especially of Drummond from W Australia supply an immense number of very distinct forms. I am anxiously expecting yours as I have no doubt they with Browns which I have not yet examine will make still further additions.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. </seg>he Australian collections of Robert Brown (1773-1858) at the British Museum.</p>
               </note> I am now at Gompholobium &amp; <name key="Burtonia">Burtonia</name> two genera most intimately connected but still as far as I have gone must be technically separated, like Oxylobium and <name key="Gastrolobium">Gastrolobium</name> by the number of ovules Where there is a tenable distinction either in habit or character we must I think keep up large genera <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">universally adopted</hi>
               </seg> — otherwise no-one would follow us, and our changes only overload synonymy. In this view <name key="Gompholobium%20foliolosum">Gompholobium foliolosum</name>, subulatum (your stenophyllum) and polyzygum must go into <name key="Burtonia">Burtonia</name>. On the other hand I think that some <name key="Burtonia">Burtonia</name>s must be excluded but I have not yet finished them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You asked me whether I could send you a copy of the <name key="Papilionaceae">Papilionaceae</name> of Martius's Flora Brasiliensis which I should have most gladly done if I had one that I could spare — but I had only <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">one</hi>
               </seg> copy for myself which I am obliged to keep for reference — and it is a very expensive work to buy. I think the whole Flora Brasiliensis is one that the Melbourne Library ought to procure.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Australian mail came in yesterday but no letters delivered from you I therefore now close this to save the Southampton mail this being overweight for Marseilles</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr F. Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I think <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name> (including Acacia) will make under 1000 sp. — My 2d vol will hold at least 1200 — perhaps more. I can therefore take in <name key="Rosaceae">Rosaceae</name>
               <name key="Saxifrageae">Saxifrageae</name>
               <name key="Lythraceae">Lythraceae</name> &amp; allied families leaving <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> for the 3d. I shall be glad to have your specimens as soon as convenient in order to print next spring</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">May 19</p>
